WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:08.000
From the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

00:00:08.000 --> 00:00:15.000
Today is December 13th, 2015. This is David Cline from the History Department and Virginia Tech,

00:00:15.000 --> 00:00:20.000
and also working with the Southern Oral History Program at the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill.

00:00:20.000 --> 00:00:25.000
I'm here for the Civil Rights History Project of the Library of Congress,

00:00:25.000 --> 00:00:31.000
the Smithsonian's National Museum of African American History and Culture and the Southern Oral History Program.

00:00:31.000 --> 00:00:38.000
And very honored to be here today with Joseph and Embry Howell and what I would ask you to do,

00:00:38.000 --> 00:00:43.000
oh, one note, I want to acknowledge a couple of other people in the room before I have you introduce yourselves.

00:00:43.000 --> 00:00:52.000
So we have John Bishop from Media Generation behind the camera and also helping us out today is Guhashankar from the Library of Congress.

00:00:52.000 --> 00:01:00.000
So now what I would ask you to do is, the only time I'm going to script you at all today is to ask you to use a full sentence to introduce yourself.

00:01:00.000 --> 00:01:08.000
Each of you, I am more my name is, and introduce yourself. And then what we're going to do is just have a conversation.

00:01:08.000 --> 00:01:19.000
We'll talk a bit about each of your childhoods and sort of what may have informed you leading up to involvement later in the movement,

00:01:19.000 --> 00:01:22.000
and then we'll talk about your activity. So whoever wants to go first.

00:01:22.000 --> 00:01:24.000
Oh, my name is Joe Howell.

00:01:24.000 --> 00:01:26.000
And I'm Embry Howell.

00:01:26.000 --> 00:01:31.000
Okay. And Emory, let me start with you if you could tell us a little bit about where and when you were born,

00:01:31.000 --> 00:01:33.000
and I'll ask you some questions about your child.

00:01:33.000 --> 00:01:40.000
Okay. I was born in 1945 in Bethesda, Maryland near here at suburban hospital.

00:01:40.000 --> 00:01:47.000
My father had the war had just ended, and my father was just leaving his assignment in the Navy.

00:01:47.000 --> 00:01:52.000
He actually, he had already gone back to where my family lived in Bristol, Virginia at that time,

00:01:52.000 --> 00:01:56.000
and my mother stayed here to have the baby.

00:01:56.000 --> 00:01:58.000
And so where were you raised then?

00:01:58.000 --> 00:02:04.000
So I was raised for five years in Bristol, and then my family moved to Davidson, North Carolina,

00:02:04.000 --> 00:02:08.000
where my father was treasurer of the college and ultimately president of the college.

00:02:08.000 --> 00:02:13.000
So I grew up in a very idyllic setting right on the college campus.

00:02:13.000 --> 00:02:18.000
And could you tell me a little bit about what your family was like,

00:02:18.000 --> 00:02:24.000
the values that you were raised with, sort of, you know, the benefit of hindsight and looking back,

00:02:24.000 --> 00:02:27.000
but you obviously got involved in the Civil Rights Movement.

00:02:27.000 --> 00:02:36.000
Can you see values that were instilled with you or things that you were perhaps, you know, reacting to in North Carolina?

00:02:36.000 --> 00:02:40.000
Yeah. Well, I'm from Southern Stock.

00:02:40.000 --> 00:02:45.000
We both are. My parents were both born and raised in Georgia.

00:02:45.000 --> 00:02:52.000
My father in North Georgia near Atlanta, and my mother in South Georgia, really the deep South.

00:02:52.000 --> 00:03:02.000
But they both came from what I would credit my values from very highly educated people for the South.

00:03:02.000 --> 00:03:09.000
In fact, both of my grandmother's went to college, which is very unusual for women at that time, as well as my grandfather's.

00:03:09.000 --> 00:03:16.000
And that level of education goes back into the 19th century as well.

00:03:16.000 --> 00:03:29.000
So my mother went to New York and basically went to communist meetings sometimes in the 30s and was very connected to the radicalization in the 30s.

00:03:29.000 --> 00:03:34.000
Not my father. My father was a more traditional person, but they were very accepting.

00:03:34.000 --> 00:03:41.000
My father and his presidency was influential in integrating Davidson.

00:03:41.000 --> 00:03:46.000
So the first black students who came were from Africa.

00:03:46.000 --> 00:03:53.000
And that was, you know, I mean, it's hard to believe that that wasn't until.

00:03:53.000 --> 00:03:57.000
Was that during the time you were there? 63.

00:03:57.000 --> 00:04:01.000
The very first black students, and they started with African students.

00:04:01.000 --> 00:04:13.000
And then I don't know when the first African American students came to Davidson, but it's amazing to think that when I was a child, and I went to thoroughly segregated schools.

00:04:13.000 --> 00:04:23.000
But it was a little southern town, and my friends lived across the tracks, and their parents worked in the mills in town.

00:04:23.000 --> 00:04:33.000
And I had very close friends there. So I would cross the tracks to go play with friends, and my mother, I wouldn't say it was her idea, but she didn't discourage that.

00:04:33.000 --> 00:04:44.000
So I'd say from very early years I learned that all people have value and should be treated with dignity.

00:04:44.000 --> 00:04:57.000
So, and most people were quite religious in that era, went to church, and so it was perhaps a cheering church, and was not integrated.

00:04:57.000 --> 00:05:04.000
But you got the values of love and acceptance, I think, from that as well.

00:05:04.000 --> 00:05:08.000
Did they have race relations Sunday at that point in the church?

00:05:08.000 --> 00:05:16.000
No, there was nothing like that. There was no real effort reaching across.

00:05:16.000 --> 00:05:37.000
But that started a little bit, you know, I'd say, just starting when the beginnings of the Civil Rights Movement in the early 60s, but I can't recall anything like that happening much in Davidson, Joe may [have known], because he was a student there, and he was a student radical there.

00:05:37.000 --> 00:05:49.000
But what was interesting was that we were in Southwest Georgia, which will come up later, and my grandmother, my mother was raised just a few miles from where we lived.

00:05:49.000 --> 00:06:00.000
And so, you know, there we were back in Southwest Georgia where she grew up, and she was quite accepting of us doing what we did.

00:06:00.000 --> 00:06:03.000
I hope definitely ask about that.

00:06:03.000 --> 00:06:11.000
Yeah, but Joe, if I could turn to you for a moment, and have you tell us a little bit about where you were born and raised?

00:06:11.000 --> 00:06:20.000
So, yeah, I was born in 1942 in Nashville, Tennessee, and I grew up in a suburb of Nashville called Belle Meade, which was the quote, elite neighborhood.

00:06:20.000 --> 00:06:29.000
My father was ended up being a president of a bank, and his father was the president of a bank, and it was understood that I would probably be a banker.

00:06:29.000 --> 00:06:36.000
And I went to Montgomery Bell Academy, which was a elite prep school, all boys.

00:06:36.000 --> 00:06:46.000
And this was part of the Nashville elite of a very heavy emphasis on some of the social aspects, social order.

00:06:46.000 --> 00:06:51.000
And what affected my life early on was having polio, 1952, polio, 1952, Warm Springs.

00:06:51.000 --> 00:07:11.000
I was moderately paralyzed. I spent six months in polio, 1952, Warm Springs, and I was, I missed two years of school, at homebound teacher, but I was not a part of the school of those years with growing up into very important ages of 10 and 12.

00:07:11.000 --> 00:07:25.000
And that gave me a sensitivity for people who were suffering. I never felt sorry for myself really, in that sense of being suffering, but I felt, I felt an empathy for people that I think I probably would not have felt otherwise.

00:07:25.000 --> 00:07:35.000
And if I had not had that experience, it's quite probable I never would have ended up getting involved in this in the Civil Rights Movement.

00:07:35.000 --> 00:07:38.000
So that was sort of the foundations, but I did not know growing.

00:07:38.000 --> 00:07:43.000
You remember making those kind of connections, even that, you know, or just something that you grabbed?

00:07:43.000 --> 00:07:53.000
I think I look back on it, it just sort of happened. I was always sort of a bleeding heart. It wasn't just Civil Rights, but I had a soft spot in my heart.

00:07:53.000 --> 00:08:09.000
I was bringing turkeys to poor people in high school and feeling ash. How can people live in such conditions in an area where there's such affluence?

00:08:09.000 --> 00:08:17.000
So that, I think that was a piece of it. And my parents were both very religious and very involved in the church, my mother, especially.

00:08:17.000 --> 00:08:29.000
And I think there were religious values, I think they were important as well. We were Episcopalians, and our church was near Vanderbilt, and it was a somewhat diverse congregation.

00:08:29.000 --> 00:08:33.000
And then, and you went to Davidson?

00:08:33.000 --> 00:08:34.000
I went to Davidson.

00:08:34.000 --> 00:08:36.000
And that's where you went?

00:08:36.000 --> 00:08:48.000
My senior year, after I'd gotten involved in Civil Rights Movement, we were getting to that probably in a minute, but my senior year, in Embry at that point was a mere child.

00:08:48.000 --> 00:08:54.000
I looked back on it, and I can't believe it was so young, but it was around my old college, which was moved out of town.

00:08:54.000 --> 00:08:59.000
Although, I think briefly we had met once before, but that's when we started dating.

00:08:59.000 --> 00:09:01.000
We were in a Mustang year at Davidson.

00:09:01.000 --> 00:09:03.000
You dated President's daughter?

00:09:03.000 --> 00:09:05.000
The President's daughter.

00:09:05.000 --> 00:09:11.000
And I was the controversial student on campus.

00:09:11.000 --> 00:09:15.000
So tell them about student activism at Davidson in that period.

00:09:15.000 --> 00:09:25.000
Well, yeah, I was going to get it. I meant to mention in Nashville, I did not know in Nashville what was going on at the time in 1962, in 1963, and even earlier than that.

00:09:25.000 --> 00:09:29.000
That's where a lot of the early civil rights movement was taking place.

00:09:29.000 --> 00:09:32.000
And the planning of it all, the early sit-ins were planned in Nashville.

00:09:32.000 --> 00:09:43.000
Nashville was supposed to be the first spot, but they were preempted by Greensboro, and NC A&T, and so on.

00:09:43.000 --> 00:09:45.000
But Davidson was aware of that.

00:09:45.000 --> 00:09:52.000
My freshman year, my sophomore year, where other cities, a few students participated, was very controversial.

00:09:52.000 --> 00:09:56.000
And then, and then I became sort of a big man on campus.

00:09:56.000 --> 00:10:00.000
I see a year I was president of the YMCA, which reported some bizarre reason.

00:10:00.000 --> 00:10:04.000
It was an important institution. Then at Davidson.

00:10:04.000 --> 00:10:10.000
And I was a president of ODK, which gave me a lot of social standing with a leadership fraternity.

00:10:10.000 --> 00:10:14.000
And I was in a fraternity. In fact, I was about as conformist.

00:10:14.000 --> 00:10:18.000
You could find out all the things you're supposed to do there.

00:10:18.000 --> 00:10:26.000
But the segregation piece was a sense, even a no-brainer, well, was a no-brainer, even then, in terms of the injustice.

00:10:26.000 --> 00:10:30.000
I'm even growing up, where this just doesn't make any sense.

00:10:30.000 --> 00:10:38.000
I remember having a playmate, who was named Frederick, who was my age, and we played together until a seven or eight years old.

00:10:38.000 --> 00:10:44.000
And at a certain point, my mother said, well, you and Frederick aren't going to play together anymore.

00:10:44.000 --> 00:10:48.000
And I was a black kid, obviously, who was the nephew of our housekeeper.

00:10:48.000 --> 00:10:54.000
And I just didn't understand. So someday, someday, well, you will understand.

00:10:54.000 --> 00:10:58.000
And so I went to, I remember going to a YMCA camp with a lot of kids.

00:10:58.000 --> 00:11:02.000
There were white kids from the other side of the tracks.

00:11:02.000 --> 00:11:06.000
There would be lower, quote, unquote, lower class working class white kids.

00:11:06.000 --> 00:11:18.000
Very much anti, anti black folks, which rub me, or at least my sensitivities, etc.

00:11:18.000 --> 00:11:20.000
So when you get to Davis, all this stuff is starting to happen.

00:11:20.000 --> 00:11:28.000
And we went to a conference in Bryn Mawr, called the Third Great American Revolution.

00:11:28.000 --> 00:11:33.000
It was mainly East Coast colleges. It was put on by Haverford and Bryn Mawr.

00:11:33.000 --> 00:11:37.000
And it just happened to go there with a handful of other Davidson students.

00:11:37.000 --> 00:11:41.000
I was the only senior. And all the leaders were there.

00:11:41.000 --> 00:11:47.000
I mean, CORE represented; SNCC as SCLC was there.

00:11:47.000 --> 00:11:51.000
And the headguys weren't there. The lieutenants were.

00:11:51.000 --> 00:11:53.000
This is what you're again?

00:11:53.000 --> 00:11:57.000
This was the spring of 1964.

00:11:57.000 --> 00:12:01.000
In those days, this was sort of right in the middle of the Civil Rights Movement.

00:12:01.000 --> 00:12:07.000
In those days, the message was clear. The audience, the participants were almost all white.

00:12:07.000 --> 00:12:10.000
And they were almost Ivy League, Presbyte just schools.

00:12:10.000 --> 00:12:13.000
Davidson was the only Southern school I think that was represented.

00:12:13.000 --> 00:12:17.000
And says, don't sit on the sidelines. Get involved.

00:12:17.000 --> 00:12:20.000
I mean, you can't be neutral in this.

00:12:20.000 --> 00:12:23.000
So we said, you know, we ought to do something.

00:12:23.000 --> 00:12:26.000
And also, I did have one experience that day.

00:12:26.000 --> 00:12:30.000
This was right before Freedom Summer.

00:12:30.000 --> 00:12:33.000
That's right. This was going to go free to summer of 1964.

00:12:33.000 --> 00:12:39.000
And I'd remembered the Freedom Riders had come through Davidson my sophomore year.

00:12:39.000 --> 00:12:42.000
And I sat in on a very small group of people.

00:12:42.000 --> 00:12:51.000
I remember the student Union Theological Seminary. There weren't many people describing their experiences of cattle prodders and being spat upon by these.

00:12:51.000 --> 00:12:56.000
irate white people. And I just couldn't believe this was happening in our country.

00:12:56.000 --> 00:13:00.000
But before we, it was about a five hour six hour drive to Davidson.

00:13:00.000 --> 00:13:04.000
And before we actually arrived at Davidson, which was late in the evening,

00:13:04.000 --> 00:13:07.000
we'd come up with a plan. We were going to do something.

00:13:07.000 --> 00:13:10.000
We had us let us stand up. And I was the logical figurehead.

00:13:10.000 --> 00:13:14.000
I mean, I was not an activist. And I didn't see myself as a revolutionary.

00:13:14.000 --> 00:13:19.000
But it just seemed like the right thing to do. So what are we going to do?

00:13:19.000 --> 00:13:22.000
So we said, we're going to organize on March.

00:13:22.000 --> 00:13:25.000
This is a very, this was the same time that the March of,

00:13:25.000 --> 00:13:28.000
this is, follow the March on Washington, which was in 1963.

00:13:28.000 --> 00:13:30.000
This is the spring of 1964.

00:13:30.000 --> 00:13:33.000
We're going to have the March on Charlotte.

00:13:33.000 --> 00:13:36.000
Somebody said, wait a minute. Charlotte is, you know,

00:13:36.000 --> 00:13:38.000
it's not Jackson, Mississippi or Birmingham, Alabama.

00:13:38.000 --> 00:13:42.000
They actually have fairly progressive racial policies.

00:13:42.000 --> 00:13:44.000
These, these, they felt they were.

00:13:44.000 --> 00:13:46.000
This maybe it's the March in Charlotte.

00:13:46.000 --> 00:13:51.000
But what we're going to do is collect signatures for people supporting the Civil Rights Act of 1964.

00:13:51.000 --> 00:13:57.000
At that point of 1964. And then we're going to mail the signatures to President Johnston.

00:13:57.000 --> 00:14:02.000
So we, and we, and we were going to partner with all the schools in the area that we could find.

00:14:02.000 --> 00:14:05.000
But predominantly by schools, Barber-Scotia, Johnson C. Smith,

00:14:05.000 --> 00:14:09.000
which was really the host school and several others.

00:14:09.000 --> 00:14:15.000
And I was the, ended up being the figurehead in this thing in this event.

00:14:15.000 --> 00:14:18.000
And it was quite controversial, as you can imagine.

00:14:18.000 --> 00:14:22.000
And the fact that I wasn't doing it.

00:14:22.000 --> 00:14:25.000
Way till we get the bird clock.

00:14:25.000 --> 00:14:34.000
I don't always go off at the same time.

00:14:34.000 --> 00:14:41.000
I mean, looking back on it, it seems about as innocuous as you can get.

00:14:41.000 --> 00:14:43.000
All you're doing is saying you're supporting the Civil Rights Act of 1964.

00:14:43.000 --> 00:14:47.000
But it was obviously had a symbolic meaning that went beyond that.

00:14:47.000 --> 00:14:52.000
And Davidson was the sleepy school safe places in your child.

00:14:52.000 --> 00:14:55.000
So I got, I knew that I would get a telephone call.

00:14:55.000 --> 00:14:57.000
I would get some pressure at some point.

00:14:57.000 --> 00:15:00.000
And sure enough, a few days before the March was going to start.

00:15:00.000 --> 00:15:04.000
I got a call from the president of Davidson College, and D. Grier Martin.

00:15:04.000 --> 00:15:06.000
Who had a daughter named me and Embry Martin.

00:15:06.000 --> 00:15:08.000
I did not know at the time.

00:15:08.000 --> 00:15:10.000
And inviting me into his house.

00:15:10.000 --> 00:15:14.000
I mean, it was like eight o'clock at night in his wife, Louis,

00:15:14.000 --> 00:15:16.000
greeting me at the door.

00:15:16.000 --> 00:15:17.000
And it's great.

00:15:17.000 --> 00:15:20.000
It'll be with you in just a second when in the study.

00:15:20.000 --> 00:15:25.000
And he, when we sat down, he said, Joe, I just have to tell you that there's a lot of pressure on me

00:15:25.000 --> 00:15:35.000
from the Board of Trustees and from the mayor of Charlotte to ask you to just abandon this, that's how I do it.

00:15:35.000 --> 00:15:40.000
Now, I have to also say that I can't force you to do anything.

00:15:40.000 --> 00:15:41.000
You can do what you want to do.

00:15:41.000 --> 00:15:44.000
You were very careful to point that out the outset.

00:15:44.000 --> 00:15:47.000
But he said the racial relations in Charlotte have actually been pretty good.

00:15:47.000 --> 00:15:53.000
And the feeling is it will create an image of the city that will do more harm and good

00:15:53.000 --> 00:15:56.000
because it will distort the picture.

00:15:56.000 --> 00:15:58.000
And then you've already made your point.

00:15:58.000 --> 00:16:02.000
So why don't you just abandon it and move on.

00:16:02.000 --> 00:16:05.000
But you don't have to.

00:16:05.000 --> 00:16:10.000
And I could get a thought of a hint of a slight net a wink.

00:16:10.000 --> 00:16:13.000
But I had the sense that he was actually supporting this.

00:16:13.000 --> 00:16:17.000
And it turns out behind the scenes he was doing a lot to make integration happen.

00:16:17.000 --> 00:16:21.000
And Davidson, which had already started with [the] foreign students.

00:16:21.000 --> 00:16:29.000
And then a few years later, two or three years later, the American students were at Davidson as well, American Black students.

00:16:29.000 --> 00:16:34.000
So we did the March and got a lot of coverage.

00:16:34.000 --> 00:16:37.000
One of ending and getting in the wire services picked it up.

00:16:37.000 --> 00:16:48.000
And the headlines of the conservative newspaper in Nashville had banker's son leads rights March.

00:16:48.000 --> 00:16:51.000
So that got everybody's attention.

00:16:51.000 --> 00:16:58.000
Joseph T. Howell III, which is me, the son of Joseph T. Howell Jr., president of Nashville City Banks,

00:16:58.000 --> 00:17:01.000
is involved in a leader of this March in Charlotte.

00:17:01.000 --> 00:17:03.000
So my parents were.

00:17:03.000 --> 00:17:08.000
Their friends, they were part of the Nashville elite cocktail party set.

00:17:08.000 --> 00:17:11.000
And people would come up and do them.

00:17:11.000 --> 00:17:14.000
And they would say, well, Carol and Joe, it's not your fault.

00:17:14.000 --> 00:17:16.000
I mean, these things do happen.

00:17:16.000 --> 00:17:19.000
And just don't blame yourself for it.

00:17:19.000 --> 00:17:21.000
And my parents were actually very supportive.

00:17:21.000 --> 00:17:23.000
And never, I never got any feedback.

00:17:23.000 --> 00:17:31.000
And finally, my mother just came out and just felt tired of this happening and say, look, we're very proud of what our son has done.

00:17:31.000 --> 00:17:35.000
And I've been going back to Nashville shortly after that.

00:17:35.000 --> 00:17:36.000
I was a bit of a pariah.

00:17:36.000 --> 00:17:43.000
My best friend's mother, when I went to see my best friend, who to play our usual game of Frisbee,

00:17:43.000 --> 00:17:47.000
met me at the door and said, you were no longer welcome in this house.

00:17:47.000 --> 00:17:50.000
You are discredit to your race into this community.

00:17:50.000 --> 00:17:55.000
And I never want to see.

00:17:55.000 --> 00:17:59.000
I didn't hurt my relationship with my good friend.

00:17:59.000 --> 00:18:04.000
But it was a real, that was a, and I feel sorry for her, really.

00:18:04.000 --> 00:18:10.000
I mean, they were, I never took that personally at all.

00:18:10.000 --> 00:18:14.000
I felt that she was a product of her time and culture.

00:18:14.000 --> 00:18:19.000
And it was then a thought of a straight jacket, as were a lot of people in those days.

00:18:19.000 --> 00:18:21.000
Because it was a controversial times.

00:18:21.000 --> 00:18:24.000
So I've just to finish this up.

00:18:24.000 --> 00:18:27.000
And in a sense, it could have been over.

00:18:27.000 --> 00:18:28.000
But we kept involved.

00:18:28.000 --> 00:18:34.000
One of, one relationship that was established was with Allard Lowenstein.

00:18:34.000 --> 00:18:39.000
And Al was at UNC State teaching history.

00:18:39.000 --> 00:18:41.000
He would send me stuff.

00:18:41.000 --> 00:18:43.000
And he would be on the back of a test.

00:18:43.000 --> 00:18:47.000
Or he would send me special delivery envelope, not a dorm.

00:18:47.000 --> 00:18:53.000
And I said, it's a mailman to be searching around the dorm for me to be a special delivery envelope

00:18:53.000 --> 00:18:54.000
with a test.

00:18:54.000 --> 00:18:56.000
And when the back of the test be scribbled,

00:18:56.000 --> 00:18:59.000
something like, give me a call, Al, something like that.

00:18:59.000 --> 00:19:02.000
So we got to know Al became almost Allard Lowenstein.

00:19:02.000 --> 00:19:05.000
Groupies, of course, he was involved in the dump Johnson movement,

00:19:05.000 --> 00:19:10.000
very close to Kennedy family, and a real progressive, brilliant guy, very interesting guy.

00:19:10.000 --> 00:19:12.000
Did he just become aware of what we were doing?

00:19:12.000 --> 00:19:16.000
Yeah, he was just going to wear me, said this, I'll just give one of the people I want to recruit.

00:19:16.000 --> 00:19:19.000
And we became friends with him and his wife Jenny.

00:19:19.000 --> 00:19:26.000
And when we moved to Washington, he was actually in our house when our first child was born.

00:19:26.000 --> 00:19:30.000
He was staying, and it was sleeping on our sofa bed.

00:19:30.000 --> 00:19:35.000
And that helped in a way when I got to Union Theological Seminary, which we'll talk, I'm sure, talking about in a minute,

00:19:35.000 --> 00:19:38.000
the Loenstein connection, everybody seemed to know Allard Lowenstein.

00:19:38.000 --> 00:19:43.000
And the movement, as he had called it, and we would all go to his apartment house

00:19:43.000 --> 00:19:48.000
and wait for him to show up two hours after he was supposed to with 50 other people.

00:19:48.000 --> 00:19:51.000
He was for those watching us who don't know about Loenstein,

00:19:51.000 --> 00:19:53.000
and 50 tell us just a little bit about him.

00:19:53.000 --> 00:19:57.000
Well, he went to University of North Carolina and became the leader of the,

00:19:57.000 --> 00:20:00.000
he was the president of the National Student Association at the time,

00:20:00.000 --> 00:20:05.000
and he went to Yale Law School, and was a movement guy progressive.

00:20:05.000 --> 00:20:10.000
And Eleanor Roosevelt was one of his, he rose very close to her.

00:20:10.000 --> 00:20:15.000
And he was like a pied piper, he had taught his dancer, and he had taught at Yale, I think, for a while.

00:20:15.000 --> 00:20:19.000
And everywhere that he taught, students gravitated to him because he was so smart,

00:20:19.000 --> 00:20:22.000
and he was such a charismatic figure.

00:20:22.000 --> 00:20:27.000
And eventually got elected to Congress before they germinated his district,

00:20:27.000 --> 00:20:30.000
and then he didn't get elected, but ran again several times,

00:20:30.000 --> 00:20:36.000
and then was tragically killed, assassinated, really by a former student who was mentally ill, named Dennis Sweeney.

00:20:36.000 --> 00:20:43.000
And the student who was mentally ill was the roommate of a good friend of ours at Union Theological Seminary,

00:20:43.000 --> 00:20:50.000
who became a pretty famous civil liberties lawyer, lives in Portland, matter of fact.

00:20:50.000 --> 00:20:55.000
So, all this sort of interconnections.

00:20:55.000 --> 00:21:03.000
So when did you start thinking about going on to Seminari?

00:21:03.000 --> 00:21:07.000
Well, I got a Rockefeller Fellowship, as many people,

00:21:07.000 --> 00:21:11.000
and which at the time was funded by the Rockefeller Foundation,

00:21:11.000 --> 00:21:15.000
to send people to Seminari who didn't have any idea what they wanted to do with their lives,

00:21:15.000 --> 00:21:18.000
and maybe some of them went in up in the church.

00:21:18.000 --> 00:21:22.000
And so, and I chose Union Theological Seminary because it was in New York City,

00:21:22.000 --> 00:21:27.000
and it was a progressive institution in Paul Tillich, and Reinhold Niebuhr had been there,

00:21:27.000 --> 00:21:33.000
it was probably the premier Protestant theological seminary in the world in those days.

00:21:33.000 --> 00:21:36.000
So I thought I'd really made it into the big leagues.

00:21:36.000 --> 00:21:42.000
And so I went that one year, and I liked it enough to stay on a second year.

00:21:42.000 --> 00:21:45.000
At which point I got somewhat disillusioned, but by the time they were till late to change,

00:21:45.000 --> 00:21:51.000
so I took a year out of Union Theological Seminary and worked something called MUST,

00:21:51.000 --> 00:21:56.000
a Metropolitan Urban Service Training William (Bill) Webber, had set up at a great year,

00:21:56.000 --> 00:21:58.000
and then finished up at Union Theological Seminary.

00:21:58.000 --> 00:22:00.000
By that time I was interested in other things.

00:22:00.000 --> 00:22:03.000
I was taking as many courses at Columbia Planning School,

00:22:03.000 --> 00:22:07.000
City Planning School, I had a job at the City Planning Department in New York,

00:22:07.000 --> 00:22:12.000
and then got a, got in Chapel Hill Planning School,

00:22:12.000 --> 00:22:15.000
and went to Chapel Hill and got a planning degree. In my life [my career has been...].

00:22:15.000 --> 00:22:19.000
Career has been developing affordable housing or senior housing.

00:22:19.000 --> 00:22:24.000
And when did you, so you, we got the, the meeting of the families, right?

00:22:24.000 --> 00:22:30.000
With, with every father, and when did you first start dating and that gets a marry?

00:22:30.000 --> 00:22:32.000
What if that fits into that story?

00:22:32.000 --> 00:22:37.000
Well, actually Joe doesn't remember me, but I remember him,

00:22:37.000 --> 00:22:41.000
which is kind of interesting to me, but you see I was much younger than Paul.

00:22:41.000 --> 00:22:48.000
I was much younger just kid around town, but we actually met,

00:22:48.000 --> 00:22:54.000
I, my first memory was being out there playing basketball and meeting you.

00:22:54.000 --> 00:22:55.000
I remember that.

00:22:55.000 --> 00:22:56.000
You do, okay?

00:22:56.000 --> 00:22:59.000
And then I remember going with my father to the Easter Sunrise Service,

00:22:59.000 --> 00:23:03.000
and Joe was speaking, because he was like this fascinating character

00:23:03.000 --> 00:23:07.000
who was doing these interesting things, you know, much older man.

00:23:07.000 --> 00:23:12.000
And then also that you had gone to work at Lower East Side and came and spoke

00:23:12.000 --> 00:23:14.000
to the Senior High Fellowship.

00:23:14.000 --> 00:23:17.000
Yeah, so yeah, I knew Joe.

00:23:17.000 --> 00:23:22.000
And I remember being, I think in my bathrobe and seeing you arrive at the front door

00:23:22.000 --> 00:23:26.000
with some kind of petition for daddy about something or other.

00:23:26.000 --> 00:23:27.000
Not to get again.

00:23:27.000 --> 00:23:31.000
So, you know, I was very familiar with Joe, and then I went off to college.

00:23:31.000 --> 00:23:36.000
And, you know, in those days, there were the women's colleges and the men's colleges.

00:23:36.000 --> 00:23:42.000
And you would have, you know, fancy dance weekend, and then guys would come for their date.

00:23:42.000 --> 00:23:46.000
So, I had another boyfriend, and Joe came along for the weekend.

00:23:46.000 --> 00:23:51.000
And so, we began to get to know each other that way, and fell in love.

00:23:51.000 --> 00:23:58.000
Then he went off to Union Theological Seminary, and we got married after my sophomore year in college.

00:23:58.000 --> 00:24:01.000
And I transferred to Barnard College.

00:24:01.000 --> 00:24:09.000
So, we lived right there on campus at Hastings Hall, and I went to Barnard and finished my degree there.

00:24:09.000 --> 00:24:11.000
And so, that's how it happened.

00:24:11.000 --> 00:24:12.000
Yeah.

00:24:12.000 --> 00:24:16.000
And then we both came down to Chapel Hill together to go to grad school.

00:24:16.000 --> 00:24:20.000
He went to urban planning school, and I went to public health school.

00:24:20.000 --> 00:24:25.000
So, we were in Chapel Hill for a while, but we came up to DC.

00:24:25.000 --> 00:24:26.000
Wonderful.

00:24:26.000 --> 00:24:33.000
So, let's stay at Union Theological Seminary just for a second, because I wanted to ask you about meeting Charles Sherrod,

00:24:33.000 --> 00:24:39.000
who would have been there while you were there soon, and how you ended up going to such a...

00:24:39.000 --> 00:24:41.000
Well, it was because of Charles Sherrod.

00:24:41.000 --> 00:24:43.000
Like everybody recruited all of us out.

00:24:43.000 --> 00:24:44.000
I can't remember.

00:24:44.000 --> 00:24:45.000
You probably remember there's like a...

00:24:45.000 --> 00:24:47.000
[Sherrod had recruited] dozens of students close to him.

00:24:47.000 --> 00:24:51.000
And he was very charismatic, and very much involved in civil rights.

00:24:51.000 --> 00:24:54.000
He'd been one of the founders of SNCC.

00:24:54.000 --> 00:24:57.000
And his area was Southwest Georgia.

00:24:57.000 --> 00:24:58.000
And he would...

00:24:58.000 --> 00:25:00.000
People that he thought of...

00:25:00.000 --> 00:25:01.000
All of us...

00:25:01.000 --> 00:25:05.000
[recruited] like-minded people that might be interested in doing this.

00:25:05.000 --> 00:25:07.000
He would approach us on the look of us right in the eyes.

00:25:07.000 --> 00:25:08.000
And I'd need your help.

00:25:08.000 --> 00:25:10.000
I'd need you down with me in Southwest Georgia.

00:25:10.000 --> 00:25:11.000
How could you say no?

00:25:11.000 --> 00:25:14.000
And we have no idea what was going on in Southwest Georgia.

00:25:14.000 --> 00:25:16.000
And I don't think he really did...

00:25:16.000 --> 00:25:19.000
Either he'd been away from it for a while, but he...

00:25:19.000 --> 00:25:22.000
I'm still not exactly sure what was...

00:25:23.000 --> 00:25:25.000
The method in the madness.

00:25:25.000 --> 00:25:28.000
But nonetheless, he recruited us.

00:25:28.000 --> 00:25:30.000
And I remember we discussed this.

00:25:30.000 --> 00:25:31.000
Something we weren't doing.

00:25:31.000 --> 00:25:33.000
People were still getting killed in those days.

00:25:33.000 --> 00:25:36.000
It was still making some risk.

00:25:36.000 --> 00:25:39.000
But I remember we looked at each other and said, yeah, this is the right thing.

00:25:39.000 --> 00:25:40.000
Big adventure together.

00:25:40.000 --> 00:25:41.000
And in the US.

00:25:41.000 --> 00:25:43.000
And in Portland, it was all, I guess, an adventure.

00:25:43.000 --> 00:25:48.000
So we signed up along with some of our good friends like Ed V. Brickialpister.

00:25:48.000 --> 00:25:49.000
From Union Theological Seminary, right?

00:25:49.000 --> 00:25:51.000
And went down to the summer of 1966.

00:25:51.000 --> 00:25:52.000
1966, right?

00:25:55.000 --> 00:25:57.000
You sort of said it's already.

00:25:57.000 --> 00:25:59.000
You didn't really know what to expect.

00:25:59.000 --> 00:26:01.000
But can you tell me about the trip down there?

00:26:01.000 --> 00:26:02.000
Well, that's right.

00:26:02.000 --> 00:26:13.000
Well, there were two things that predated the actual working in Southwest Georgia.

00:26:13.000 --> 00:26:16.000
On this trip, one was the conference we went to.

00:26:16.000 --> 00:26:18.000
We were supposed to be trained.

00:26:18.000 --> 00:26:21.000
We were just at Wake Forest.

00:26:21.000 --> 00:26:26.000
And it was sponsored by something called, gosh, I can't remember.

00:26:26.000 --> 00:26:31.000
But it was somewhat radical, Christian, ecumenical, something, an institute.

00:26:31.000 --> 00:26:32.000
That's it.

00:26:32.000 --> 00:26:33.000
That's it.

00:26:33.000 --> 00:26:35.000
And now that was awful.

00:26:35.000 --> 00:26:40.000
I mean, it was thought control, brainwashing, kind of stuff, and so that of rebelled at that point.

00:26:40.000 --> 00:26:43.000
I mean, so we didn't get, didn't help us much.

00:26:44.000 --> 00:26:49.000
Because it was not just civil rights people, it was always other people that were involved doing other things over the summer.

00:26:49.000 --> 00:26:56.000
And they were supposed to radicalize all these young Christians and take over the world with Christianity.

00:26:56.000 --> 00:27:00.000
That was a complete nutcase, I thought, [were] all the people involved.

00:27:00.000 --> 00:27:04.000
But we did meet some civil rights workers at the time.

00:27:04.000 --> 00:27:08.000
And I remember going out and they gave us some advice in terms of you always back in,

00:27:08.000 --> 00:27:17.000
so you can into a restaurant or someplace so you can run to the car and get out before they come after you can get a quick getaway.

00:27:17.000 --> 00:27:18.000
That's right.

00:27:18.000 --> 00:27:20.000
And other things like that.

00:27:20.000 --> 00:27:26.000
So we arrived in Southwest Georgia after driving all night at the SNCC office,

00:27:26.000 --> 00:27:31.000
which is located in the area of Albany, it says, it's called Harlem.

00:27:31.000 --> 00:27:37.000
And which was, in some ways, it was like, many of your home in New York Harlem.

00:27:38.000 --> 00:27:47.000
And my recollection is being met by the civil rights guys, black guys, and white t-shirts and blue jeans.

00:27:47.000 --> 00:28:00.000
And as we got out of the car, the comment, the first comment that I recall somebody making was, so welcome to Albany.

00:28:00.000 --> 00:28:03.000
So we are black panthers.

00:28:03.000 --> 00:28:12.000
You are a roosterous, which is the, you're the emblem, that's the, that's the, the, the, the mascot of the Democratic Southern Democratic Party,

00:28:12.000 --> 00:28:17.000
white Democratic Party in Lowndes County, Alabama, Alabama, in some place.

00:28:17.000 --> 00:28:20.000
Panthers eat roosters.

00:28:20.000 --> 00:28:22.000
Go home, whitey, we don't need you.

00:28:22.000 --> 00:28:24.000
So I said, oh my goodness.

00:28:24.000 --> 00:28:26.000
Here we are.

00:28:26.000 --> 00:28:30.000
Wait a minute, what's wrong with this picture? We're coming down here. We're our selfish.

00:28:30.000 --> 00:28:32.000
And we're risking our lives.

00:28:32.000 --> 00:28:35.000
And this is the, you know, we're not well with the, with open arms.

00:28:35.000 --> 00:28:43.000
And so it was quite unsettling, although that quickly, that quickly passed, although that was the sort of introduction that time times are changing.

00:28:43.000 --> 00:28:45.000
And what was going on there?

00:28:45.000 --> 00:28:53.000
The big story of that, of 1966 in Southwest Georgia was the big fight between John Lewis and Stokely Carmichael.

00:28:54.000 --> 00:28:58.000
And all this was going on behind the scenes. Charlie was right in the middle of it.

00:28:58.000 --> 00:29:01.000
But the one view, John Lewis views, that integration is the way to go.

00:29:01.000 --> 00:29:04.000
You need the white people, especially Southern white people.

00:29:04.000 --> 00:29:07.000
I mean, here we were, the only southerners down there, the only married couple.

00:29:07.000 --> 00:29:11.000
You need these people. They will, they will, they will play a role.

00:29:11.000 --> 00:29:15.000
Will the Stokely Carmichael us, a few wise, yeah, they could play a role.

00:29:15.000 --> 00:29:18.000
They played a role in the past.

00:29:18.000 --> 00:29:22.000
But we have got to be responsible for our own fate.

00:29:22.000 --> 00:29:28.000
We've got to build up the leadership and to have white people involved confuses things at this point in history.

00:29:28.000 --> 00:29:30.000
So it wasn't against us personally.

00:29:30.000 --> 00:29:33.000
But we had, we had no idea that this was going on.

00:29:33.000 --> 00:29:36.000
We didn't know that Charlie was struggling with all this.

00:29:36.000 --> 00:29:45.000
And so that, that played out in part in terms of how, where we got placed and what we did in and played out throughout the whole summer.

00:29:45.000 --> 00:29:51.000
The split between people who were really gun-ho and really wanted to make a difference.

00:29:51.000 --> 00:30:05.000
And yet people, the ambivalence of, felt by many of the grassroots black civil rights workers that saw us as a threat in, as people who's time has come and passed in terms of where the movement was.

00:30:05.000 --> 00:30:10.000
It was that summer that Stokely Carmichael Carmichael and Willie Ricks stayed that in name, right?

00:30:10.000 --> 00:30:13.000
That's right. He was, I mean, he was almost to the day.

00:30:13.000 --> 00:30:24.000
You know, it's interesting, though. I don't remember those statements. They might not, I was treated kind of with kid gloves.

00:30:24.000 --> 00:30:35.000
I was an unusual person. This white, southern female. Most of the people had never met anyone like me.

00:30:35.000 --> 00:30:45.000
And the guys were always extremely polite and respectful to me. I never was spoken to harshly the entire summer.

00:30:45.000 --> 00:30:55.000
So I don't, if I was there, I don't recall it. I'm sure it happened. But I think they talked to Joe that way.

00:30:55.000 --> 00:31:03.000
What about your, every year, Georgia roots in an essence, this, I mean, you would never live there, but coming back to a place that was a problem.

00:31:03.000 --> 00:31:17.000
I had spent time in Georgia as a child. I think it was actually helpful. [as transcribed].

00:31:17.000 --> 00:31:28.000
Because really, we were raised in fairly close proximity to black people and had a fair amount of contact with them.

00:31:28.000 --> 00:31:44.000
We liked the same kind of food. We spoke a lot, you know, the same way. And we understood each other well. And I think it allowed us to not necessarily with the civil rights workers because they were often not from there.

00:31:44.000 --> 00:32:01.000
But with local people. So I never had any sense of a strangement in that way. Of course, we couldn't relate to the white people in the community.

00:32:01.000 --> 00:32:13.000
So if they saw us walking down the street, [a white woman initially stopped to give her a ride, then refused once she realized who Embry was — i.e., a SNCC-affiliated white outsider].

00:32:13.000 --> 00:32:16.000
So we never had contact with the white people.

00:32:16.000 --> 00:32:32.000
We had a serious infection when I was down there. And I couldn't see the black doctor. I had to go to a white doctor because it was just unheard of.

00:32:32.000 --> 00:32:41.000
That was a complete separate. But that was struck me and kind of strange.

00:32:41.000 --> 00:32:51.000
I remember when you wanted to get your hair cut. My hair didn't matter because we had that long hair in those days. But they had never cut anybody's hair like that.

00:32:51.000 --> 00:32:55.000
Yeah, that's probably one of the best hair cut I've ever.

00:32:55.000 --> 00:33:03.000
I did go into the black barbershop. You didn't want to go into the black barbershop. They were very reluctant to do it, but they did.

00:33:03.000 --> 00:33:16.000
So tell me about living within the black community, then, and the family that you got to know. And maybe before that, how difficult it was for a family to be found at first for you all to live there?

00:33:16.000 --> 00:33:20.000
So that was the big issue. It's what they're going to do with us. In fact, we were married couple.

